segments.text: This is Deborah Beale, and I'm interviewing Dr. Michael Pustay on the history of Texas Engineering Experiment Station.
The date is June 11, 1984.
And what I'd first like to start with is a little biographical sketch of you and how you came to A&M.
Let's start with education as one of the best places to start.
Well, I'm a C minor graduate working in economics at Washington University and 69 in Dublin.
Master's of philosophy and PhD in economics from Yale in 1973.
I taught at Purdue for five years and Bowling Green for two years.
and I've been in there for four years.
I guess I've been the head of the business and technology research division for three years.
I've been also the research coordinator for research and technology business for three years or two.
We're set up together.
We're set up together.
So I basically work two things.
I'm a member of the business and public policy group in the department of management.

in the College of Business, which makes, and I'm also an associate professor in basically the DPD group of colleges, and a group of economists and lawyers who look at the interface between business and government, dealing with that's one of the, the government,
is one of the major determinants of profitability in business strategies.
So it's important to provide some indication to business students as to how the public sector and the private sector interact.
How did you make the transition to maintenance management?
I don't think there's that strong of a boundary.
My two previous affiliations were in econ departments that were part of colleges of business.
So it's really not been a very big transition.
I can do what I want to do.
The basic criterion is that I
One half of me has got to continue my own research agenda, which I've been doing, specializing in regulation of transportation, effective regulation, deregulation, or performance of those industries.
So I'm not doing anything differently than I would have been doing, and that I hadn't been doing.
So it's not that big of a deal.
The establishment of the research
organization within the College of Business and the Teens Division.
How did that come about?
I'm not totally sure, but certainly one impetus was Bill Mobley's going from department head of management to associate dean in the college.
When Mobley came in, he and I came in at the same time in August of 1980, that summer of 1980.
Mobley had a fairly extensive record as a funded researcher, doing a lot of work in the Office of Medical Research.
The college was under-resourced.
didn't have as many resources as needed or needs.
And one of the things that Bill identified as a means of solving the resource problem is to fund the research area.
I don't think that the college had a particularly extensive record of funding research activity up until that point.
When I came here, I came with two grants, two contracts from the Department of Transportation and the Small Business Administration.
And I think Bill, and at that same time, Bill and two members of the management department were proposing also, you know, research, which had gotten funded.
And that, I think, was the majority of the funding in the college.
So I guess I'm trying to, in a long-winded fashion, try to say that Bill viewed funded research as an opportunity for the college to generate resources.
He had made that an objective of the college, excuse me, of the department when it became department head.
When he became Associate Dean, I had the suspicion that he mentioned to Ben Dean and Bill Hughes that this is one area that we need to fund the research.
We need to promote funded research at the college level as it reduces our own resources.
I think that that is the impetus for the creation
of the college research board position.
Basically, simultaneously, the college decided that one direction, one area that identified as important to the state, important to the business disciplines,
in an area that really hadn't been tapped by the College of Business was the interface between business and engineering, particularly with regard to technology transfer.
the whole general question of, we've got this new technology out there, how do we integrate that into our business community?
And we felt that, you know, very natural linkage with the College of Engineering, in that regard.
In some sense, that's what the tease is, in some sense, set up to do that kind of thing.
Bill Houston and Skip Porter got along, get along very well.
I think they share some common visions.
Certainly, you know,

It was a piece of evidence that came after that was that how do we get a proper, you know, further step with this notion of how do we take technology, how do we do the engineering, how do we get things in the workplace?
And so BATTER developed a very, very reasonably, or BATTER developed, for the most part, sort of that sort of vision that was shined upon the AFCRA principal architecture.
That's what it's called, battered?
Well, we call it battered.
What are the major funding things through teams at this point in your vision?
We've got two office-enabled research contracts.
We're in the third year of one that's in jargon terms called transition and socialization.
And basically what that means is when people are either leaving more internal jobs or they're changing or transferring to an organization, how do you facilitate that transition?
Obviously that's a problem of great importance to the military, sending people every two years, every three years to a tour of duty, sometimes with their families, sometimes without.
How do you transfer them, get them up to speed, integrate them into the community, get them knowledge about their job?
So it's a natural question of concern to the opposite end of research.
It clearly is a question of interest to the business community, since the business community transfers people as well.
And it's in great interest just from its basic research perspective in the college, in terms of how to organize and manage a school, and what's the psychology of it, what's the management of it.
What impact does it have on the national performance?
Does it work out well to spend X dollars to fly the wives in for a preliminary trip, or is it not worth it to panoply the questions that are being asked?
In general, the college has tried to stress a way called the lean, lean research, which is the research that generates resources.
And that is, in a lean, lean sense, that at least leads to
published research in professional reference journals.
So the college is a very strong research organization.
In essence, we really don't want to .
There's a strong encouragement for faculty to publish in professional journals, and we don't particularly
Walk them through this.
Praise the Lord.
It's much better for all parties concerned.
Whatever funded research they do also leads to publications, peer-reviewed journals.
So that's where the lean-in comes in.
O&R would be a premier example of lean-in research, because it does generate the sources, and it does .
MS.
Generating more resources?
Well, generating resources, I mean, in the sense that it provides release time to faculty, to the researchers, to the grad students.
The grants, et cetera.
The grants, et cetera.
Of course, to the extent that you do that work well, you can generate other things.
Hello, Mike, who's that?
All right.
I bet they're waiting on it.
So it generates more resources.

provides to the extent that you do a piece of funded research well, allows you to go back and sponsor other sponsors and get more research and a couple of support, to the extent that you can generate more publications, it gives you that much more of a professional reputation.
But again, it makes it easier to .
Is most of the sponsored research coming from government sources or from ?
It's certainly the bulk of the dollars.
That O&R grant was, what does it say, we're in the third year of that, and it's a little less than 300,000 dollars, about $100,000 each year.
We have another O&R grant that we're in the first year of, we're studying organizations' information processing system.
and that's about
$150,000 of support from the Department of Transportation with the trucking deregulation.
About 60,000 from the Small Business Administration with the trucking deregulation.
That's the Deere Direct Line.
Right.
And we've had about 60,000 from the Small Business Administration with the
financial deregulation of financial markets and how it affects small value markets.
And we have some indication that we may have additional funds there.
We've got another proposal in to the Office of Naval Research from two members of the initial team.
going to look at performance feedback of the .
Where you get a notion when you do a good job, you .
Those are the biggest dollar amounts.
But I guess about $100,000 a month called industrial development .
There was a research division of TEAS that was merged into us about two years ago.
trying to assess the strengths and weaknesses of local communities and in terms of their industrial development potential.
I'm trying to give them this notion of what kinds of firms they should be targeting and what types of
and also what can they do to overcome some of the weaknesses, sort of like strategic marketing or strategic management.
No, those things are on a fee basis to the communities.
Yes.
They're not particularly lucrative from our perspective.
There is sort of service component to it, but they're on a fee basis.
In terms of publishing, how does that work?
Those generally, those are not research.
Those generally do not have a research publication component to them.
As a result, we tend to develop as a core of graduate students, cadres of graduate students who do that work under the faculty supervision.
We view that more as a training exercise for PhD students.
Particularly, we have a couple in the market that are more interested in that.
So they view it as a service market.
It provides them support.
It provides them a little bit of visibility.
It also provides them with kind of a dry run for the dissertation.
In essence, having to go out there and find out what the data sources are and having to be able to get information from them.
So those are a variety, those are valuable research skills which are
which fit very nicely with the pedagogical mission of college.
Have the graduate students been doing this for years?
This isn't just a new model.
Well, in the college they've been doing it for, say, two years now, in the past, before it was part of us, I think they were using full-time staff.
I think they had a problem.
that they were having trouble getting enough work, given the price they had to charge on their full-time staff.
When did they move to the Center for Strategic Technology and they moved it back out?
I think it was independent of Media, Industry, and Technology.
I think it moved out and then it moved to us.
Well, it had been around since the blues, that beginning division.
I've been told that division at one time made a lot of money.
Oh, it did.
In the 50s it was going crazy.
And I don't know if you were aware that they were doing freight rate studies.
In 1939, the state of Texas commissioned them to do freight rate studies because they were bringing
suits in front of the ICC for discriminatory freight rates.
And so they did tons of freight rate studies of different things in Texas and comparative to other states in that period.
And this was the same group of people.
And then they grew into the industrial community surveys from that.
I was told the industrial community surveys were quite lucrative back when the federal government was dumping a lot of money into community planning.
They would give a panel $50,000 and say, go plan.
And they'd say, well, we don't have a plan.
So what they would do is turn around and commission industrial economics to do a survey.
But apparently that money's drying up.
So we kind of got it that it was not the most lucrative activity.
But you think you've been able to turn it into something a little different?
Well, I think we've managed to make it into something useful for the college and for the communities of Texas.
We've had relatively low, at lower cost than both parties.
Where it's going to go, it's all up to you.
We've also actually turned it into a vehicle for publishing directories.
We've got two directories now.
We've got one directory out in the Middle East, the choice is in the press.
One is an industrial parks directory, which we think will be useful for community planning for those who are interested in industrial development.
Is that the only thing that came with the TEAS division?
Basically.
You're grinning.
What it came with was one secretary who had become a staff member.
He came with a few desks, and we got a 1980 Chevrolet out of it, and an out-motor board, possibly.
A hearty handshake.
Yeah, thank you for taking that off their hands.
Well, you know, again, you get into his idiosyncrasies of history, but the dean at the time was Bill Muse, who was... Hello?
You were talking about the idiosyncrasies taking off their hands.
Oh, that Bill Muse was...
I'm very concerned about local development.

The vice president of the local chamber of commerce for industrial development, he felt at this stage that the college's development would be very useful to start to build outreach programs in the community.
So he was very enthusiastic about bringing
I guess, apparently, a couple of years previously, or maybe not a couple of years previously, we had talked before about setting up a linkage between the college and the teams.
that industrial economics was considered as one of the possible vehicles.
But I think when you were talking about going to the Center, I mean, the Center for Strategic Technology was going to give up industrial economics.
Apparently there was some consideration just at the beginning of the College of Business at that point.
I think John Roberts wrote a couple of impassioned memoirs saying, you know, let me have a chance to run it.
gave him a shot.
That's something with idiosyncrasies.
In some sense, that was part of Bill Muse's vision of how he wanted the college to develop.
What do you see as Tease's role in the College of Business Research?

I'm not sure I phrased it quite that way, but I guess I would say that I think that there is an overlap, a considerable overlap in interest of TEAS's, the College of Engineering, and the College of Business' research missions that, especially as the state of Texas moves away from energy,
and natural resources-based economy to a more high-tech economy, which is currently the governor's dream and other political actors' opinions as well.
To the extent that Texas is going to pull it off, we're going to have to marry business and science.
We're going to have to be able to do the research.
in terms of the technology, but you have to also be able to deliver it in terms of providing the proper business program, proper opportunities for businesses to locate you and to develop you.
And I would view the College of Business as providing some important insights into that.
There's also a significant research overlap just in terms of what between two colleges, especially in our business and health department.
We've got the computer science department, there's also a business computer science department.
Industrial engineering does a fair amount of applied statistical
problems, as does organic farming, applying statistics to business decision making, applied to engineering decision making.
In the management department, they've got, you know, we have industrial relations and personnel practices.
They've got a counterpart over engineering.
So there's actually a fairly large overlap in the programs of the two colleges.
to pull the two researcher groups together at all, or is this the hope for the future?
Well, the research has been pulled together on an ad hoc basis.
In industrial engineering, we've created decision support, decision support biotech, and a couple of our researchers were on the ground where they are helping to develop that.
In terms of InVet, which Chris Porter is talking about InVet, the College of Business has been a major provider of human resources for InVet.
Well, I'd say about $140,000.
I know that they're paying about $140,000 to the college this year in various forms, which would be about $3,000 or $4,000.
Okay.
For the Invent?
Is Invent a win-win?
From the viewpoint of publications, not necessarily.
That is a problem.
From the viewpoint of student development, it's a terrific opportunity.
I'm going to try and use the student development that way.

If we can get our students into the process, and they are to a certain extent, learning the screening of inventions, the development of business plans, the marketing analysis, those would be extremely good.
in terms of faculty research and publications, it's a bit more conjectural.
We've gotten a few publications out of it, but not as many as we would like to, or not as many as we would need to .
That's a good question.

It's, you know, it sounds like a great idea, but with the publisher parish problems, it's... What we've tried to do is communicate to both our faculty, well, I think our faculty, but to communicate to them that if we want to have a long-term, near-term relationship,
It really has to be winning for our faculty.
We can't ask people to go over there and sacrifice their careers.
So we've been trying to put it on what I would call teaching a buyout basis.
If someone works over for Invent, that they get compensated as if they were teaching.

Generally, I think that when we pay someone to teach, say during the academic year, normally for every hour that he's in the classroom, he or she is in the classroom, that person has an hour outside of the classroom to do it.
Now you know what I do as research board.
You're talking about the pay.
That normally faculty, when you're on an academic,

but we view them as this is kind of a gross term, that they put an hour in in the classroom and the classroom related activities, and then they have an hour of free time, which we would hope that they would be involved in doing their own research and or in well, departmental citizenship, interviewing their job candidates, et cetera, et cetera.
If Invent, to make it win-win for Invent, Invent's basically got a treat-out back in the same room.
And for every hour they work over there, they've got to have an hour to do their research.
It's for the professional development.
For the professional development.
In the short run, Invent can go to people and say,
We're going to pay you 40 hours, you have to work for a year.
They can do that.
They're going to view themselves, they're going to wind up being the supplier of last markets, or excuse me, the employer of last markets among the factory.
I think that's counterproductive as far as the innovation is concerned.
I think they're generally understandable.
At that point, we get it to where it's really neutral.
Right.
What are your responsibilities besides answering phones?
Well, the...
The two objectives are to promote the research activities of the college and to generate the resources necessary to accomplish the research.
Objective two leads back to objective one.
It's basically to simplify.
The college, I think, has a pretty clear goal of wanting to crack the top five public universities.
among public universities, it wants to be the top five business schools in the country.
and to achieve that objective we've got to, and one of the means of achieving that objective is to increase our prominence in research.
And to that extent we have to find resources to support our researchers.
The dean is devoting a fair amount of his time to external development of the fundraising.

which a large chunk of that will be delegated to providing faculty support, faculty summer, faculty summer support, support for research assistance, but it's all going to go back, in essence, to promote research.
The TEAS connection, we feel, is a mechanism for promoting research.
Funded research is a mechanism for promoting research.
Are you not only relying on TEAS for funded research?
Are you going to the research foundation?
Well, realize that TEAS does a couple things.
One, TEAS does provide us with certain financial resources.
Secondly, TEAS does contract administration.
It administers the contracts and provides all the support services that are necessary.
The Research Foundation does some of that as well, and also the Division where TEAS and the Research Foundation also work together.
So TEAS provides some financial support.
TEAS also provides all that personal support services.
TEAS also provides some leadership and some leadership.
I wouldn't put the College of Business in a follower relationship to TEAS, but I think that there's a general feeling that
So, do you pretty well, in terms of going after money, is it up to the professors themselves
you are doing, or is it something that TEAS does, comes in and says, hey, this is available?
There's a variety of mechanisms.
I would imagine this is universal throughout all the green communities.
Some of the research is simply faculty-driven.
Professors say, I'm interested in this.
It comes to me.
Where can I get money for this?
We'll tell them about this agency, this agency, this agency, our possible possibilities, write a report for them, write a paper for us, and so on.
Some we get from the research foundation.
They send out lists of all our RFPs from the federal government who request proposals.
We will give the RFP, then distribute to our faculty and say, if you're interested in this one,
your order for you.
Occasionally, T's will come to us and say, hey, we've got an idea that the polls are not written.
Can you get somebody to
For example, I was talking to Boeing Computing Systems about doing some research on Class 6 computers.
And they said, well, we've got the engineers involved, but we need someone who's interested in this community.
And I was telling them about marketing.
Can you locate someone for us?
And so I located someone.
There are times, at least they've got another one, where they think the Air Force is going to let our contract for our materials lab are done, and they ask us if we could help them.
Actually, it's called Manufacturing Sciences.
If we could provide them with some people like that, too.
We were going to be writing a proposal to IBM, and it's going to be useful for us to demonstrate that we've got a multidisciplinary approach to it.
And we'll go to them and say, and I'll probably go to Bruce McCormick, head of computer science, or to Eric Charles of the Academy of Industrial Engineering and say, hey,
We need some help from you guys to round out what's possible and presumptions that they'll help us.
So it's a two-way street regarding who helps who.
It is only where the research comes from or how it's initiated that really varies across the spectrum.
But is your job also to cancel the other
I would view myself as, in some sense, a repository for information, a dispenser of information.
Since all information, one way or another,
conceptualizing is that all information about research flows into me and then I disperse it to those things that's useful information.
Information is costly.
Transmitting information is costly.
If you can centralize that function, there are some advantages.

When people have problems with a research project they've already got, because they've got a problem with a research foundation or they've run into a bureaucratic staff who they'll come to me and I'll figure out who they should talk to.
If someone's interested in writing a proposal, I'll try and help them out, even if it's locating a sponsor or telling them what the situation is, or perhaps dissuading them.
I am in charge, I would say, of some career counseling responsibilities, which are basically given to me by the dean.
For example,
We view funded research as being desirable, as rounding out a professor's retail, but we think it's a higher risk activity to them, especially the writing of the results.
And we certainly do not want to encourage our students to engage.
We'd much rather they spent their time lining their dissertation, getting a couple articles out of it, than engaging in a blind proposal to the NSF.
One of the things I do each year is have an orientation session.
We're just in funded research, but this really isn't for you.
This perhaps is not for you at this stage in your career.
Crank out the easy ones first.
Crank out the easy ones first.
Part of this is that in a funded research group, reputation helps.
And if you're an unproven assistant professor, you're swimming upstream.
It's a high enough risk activity to begin with, and the odds are stacked against you even more.
We just don't want people to misinterpret the signals.
They read in the faculty guidelines for evaluation that funded research are desirable.
We want them to say, oh, I've got to get to the funding restriction.
That's fine once you've made a reputation.
If you want to write a proposal, that's fine.
But we're not going to force you to.
We don't force anybody to do anything.
But we don't want to even say that.
We're not encouraging you.
We want you to think that you've got to do it.
Just build your record, and when you feel comfortable with it, deal with it, and try to write a proposal for it.
No proposal before it's done.
As head of the division, are you on Matisse payroll part-time?
Yes.
Is it half-time?
It's about half-time.
And...
Do you think this, then releasing, giving release time to you, essentially, to service this function as a repository of information, does that help the department and the school
Not necessarily because it's you, but because... Well, I would hope so.
And if I didn't think it was a useful expenditure of funds, I would suggest, you know, I would recommend that we would abolish the position.
In other words, you're not getting ready to recommend to abolish the position.
No, I'm not... No, I think in fact that the...
I think in fact that...
I would probably recommend that there are more things that are necessary to be done.
But the experiment is succeeding?
I think the experiment is succeeding.
I think it was clear it was a wise decision three years ago to give someone responsibility for basically looking after research.
Before there was no real ombudsman for research.
I think it's been very useful.

Have, you know, this has only been around for three years, but have there been any major economic or business orientation changes that have changed the amount of funding from either private or public sources?
Well, I think we've hit upon it.
We really haven't been just as long enough to have a consistent track record.
I mean, we don't know.
I think that...
I think last year we put a major push on to get resources from, to get more private resources, more private companies.
And we found that that was a lousy time.
Time was lousy given what the business cycle was.
So that was not particularly successful.
I think we also found that we were premature.
We thought that the people out there who were, we found out that Texas A&M, we have a college of business research.
That's terrific.
We're really glad to hear about it.
That took us down a peg and we realized that we have some, we have a PR problem that we're not as well known as we thought we should be.
Our department's, the college is very young, I think it started in the sixties.
Our department's generally learned very well, research-wise.
I think the management department was ranked third in a recent survey of academy management from public universities, after Elmore and Berkley.
So we're starting to see indications that our research program is .
Generally, we haven't gotten any established scholars because we've had a tendency to build from the bottom.
So we've got very young people.
The only part we've really got is really, I guess we've got Pete Rose and Don Frey and Finian Scott.
We've got very established scholars.
We think our better days are ahead of us.
I think I lost myself there.
You were talking about the development and the question was about whether there were any cycles.
What we found was that we thought it was a cycle in the sense that we ran into trouble in the last business cycle.
You hit the wrong one.
But we also found that we were not as well known as we thought we were.
So we decided we better take a step back and do a little more work.
So we created what we call the research newsletter, which we're sending out to...
I think about 1,000 chief executive officers in Texas and national companies, all new deans of colleges and businesses in the country, and a variety of other mailing lists that are out there.
That's the business college.
It's a newsletter, isn't it?
Right.
And a T is connected to it.
Well, actually, it's jointly put out by Batter and not the College of Business.
A lot of our stuff is jointly put out by Batter and the College of Business, because I've got full of his heads up.

So a lot of times, we talk about the College of Business, and it really refers back to Batter, because Batter is, in some sense, a 100% wholly owned subsidiary of the College of Business, which is also owned by Keyes.
So we're putting out the newsletter just now.
Inform people that, yes, we are indeed doing some research.
We're sending out the newsletter to all the Texas newspapers and magazines.
Just at the end of it, we build them on each of our community leaders the notion that, yes, this is a place we're working on.
That was our first attempt to overcome that.
the deficiency that we saw in the problem recognition.
So I think TEAS itself is having the same problem.
And they've been trying to address it for a few years now.
Anything but agriculture here, I think, is the problem.
Well, the folks in Ag are doing a very good job.
They've been at it for a long time.
They've been at it for longer, but they've done a good job.
And of course, having county extension in each of the counties is helpful.
We're not going to do that.
The history department's not going to do that, so you've got to find other mechanisms.
The state's not going to fund it either.
Is there anything else that you'd like to say about your relationship with teens or the business department's relationship with teens that we haven't covered?
Not often.
I guess I've rambled on to be able to richer answer your questions.
Yeah, I'm sure.
It's much better than yesterday.
I kind of thought that.
I guess I'd say that the relationship
has been a very fruitful one.
I think it will continue to be fruitful in both parties.
I think it's a natural marriage of the interests of the college business and the teams.
I think it will promote the mission of both
groups.
I think it will help TEAS in terms of its service to the state of Texas.
It will help the College of Business in terms of its instructional mission and its teaching and its service mission.
I think we're looking to go on and continue to evolve.
But generally, I think a wealth organization would less include leadership in people innovation.
I mean, it's important.
And frankly, three years ago, or four years ago, before I came here, they asked me, what do I think about the management department?
I guess economics or economists, by training, look at inputs and outputs and how the inputs are transforming the output.
Outputs are kind of a black box.
Economists don't concern themselves about that.
Reality.
Yeah.
And I never really thought about that until I got here.
Now I'm beginning to realize that what goes on in the black box is important.
And one of the things that goes on in the black box is leadership.
Before leadership, in my mind, was a touchy-feely buzzword that fed me.
I still can't define it, but it's kind of like you know it when you see it.
You know it when you're involved.
And I think both organizations are doing it.
